{"updated_at": {"date": {"d": "11", "m": "03", "Y": "2026"}, "time": {"H": "08", "M": "27", "S": "21"}}, "news": [{"title": "Uttar Pradesh government allocates \u20b9425 crore for townships in eight cities", "para": "Uttar Pradesh government has allocated Rs 425 crore for developing new townships in eight key cities, including Bareilly and Varanasi. This seed capital, under the Chief Minister New Township Scheme, aims to facilitate planned urban growth and improve housing for a growing population. The government will fund up to 50% of land acquisition costs.", "href": "https://realty.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/infrastructure/uttar-pradesh-invests-425-crore-in-new-townships-across-eight-cities/129432135?utm_source=newslisting&utm_medium=latestNews", "img": "data:image/png;base64, ", "img-src": "https://etimg.etb2bimg.com/thumb/img-size-69540/129432135.cms?width=150&height=112", "tag": "infrastructure"}, {"title": "Maharashtra: New stamp duty penalty effective from January 1 this year", "para": "A significant increase in the penalty for property documents executed without sufficient stamp duty is now in effect from January 1, 2026. The revised penalty, raised to Rs1 lakh from Rs5,000, aims to curb deliberate underpayment of stamp duty. This amendment strengthens action against those evading required stamp duty on property transactions.", "href": "https://realty.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/regulatory/maharashtra-implements-new-rs1-lakh-stamp-duty-penalty-from-january-2026/129432076?utm_source=newslisting&utm_medium=latestNews", "img": "data:image/png;base64, ", "img-src": "https://etimg.etb2bimg.com/thumb/img-size-42916/129432076.cms?width=150&height=112", "tag": "regulatory"}, {"title": "Chandigarh administration proposes structured penalties, clearer definitions of property categories", "para": "Chandigarh is set to overhaul building violation and property misuse regulations by amending the Capital of Punjab (Development and Regulation) Act, 1952. New definitions for property categories, structured penalties capped at 20% of property value, and enhanced administrative powers are being introduced.  Appeals will now be streamlined to the chief administrator within 30 days.", "href": "https://realty.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/industry/chandigarh-administration-proposes-major-changes-to-building-regulations-and-penalties/129431989?utm_source=newslisting&utm_medium=latestNews", "img": "data:image/png;base64, ", "img-src": "https://etimg.etb2bimg.com/thumb/img-size-16932/129431989.cms?width=150&height=112", "tag": "industry"}]}